  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins review Halina Reijn's erotic-thriller-comedy 'Babygirl,' then drag Nicole Kidman's four-decade filmography across a red-yellow-green board to build her Hall of Fame; Sean closes with a conversation with Reijn.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Babygirl’",
      "note": "Kidman and Harris Dickinson, dom and sub",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Babygirl",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Reijn's third feature: Kidman is a robotics-company CEO who risks career and marriage on a submissive affair with an intern (Harris Dickinson, opposite Antonio Banderas as her husband). The hosts read it as an erotic thriller played as a comedy of manners: no murder, no Sharon Stone, just the milk scene, the rave, and 'good girl.' Both are pro, both flag underdeveloped corporate edges and a too-tidy ending; Amanda ties it to 'Eyes Wide Shut' and the year's other aging-woman movie, 'The Substance.'"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "halloffame",
      "heading": "The Nicole Kidman Hall of Fame",
      "note": "ten inductees: nine films plus ‘Big Little Lies,’ the first TV title ever let in",
      "honoree": "Nicole Kidman",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Dead Calm",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "Her 1989 breakthrough, Philip Noyce's boat thriller with Sam Neill and Billy Zane. Yellowed on air, then pulled in as a final pick."
        },
        {
          "title": "To Die For",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "Sean's favorite Kidman performance and, he argues, her best: Gus Van Sant's fame satire. The room's first 'hard green.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Practical Magic",
          "year": 1998,
          "note": "The beloved Sandra Bullock witch movie; the hosts conceded the fandom and let it in."
        },
        {
          "title": "Eyes Wide Shut",
          "year": 1999,
          "note": "Kubrick's last film; her alluring, vulnerable turn read as the throughline to 'Babygirl.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Moulin Rouge!",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Her widest-audience breakout and an Oscar nod. Sean calls it the most annoying movie ever made; everyone else in the room overruled him."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Others",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Amenábar's ghost story, released the same year as 'Moulin Rouge!': her reserve at its best."
        },
        {
          "title": "Birth",
          "year": 2004,
          "note": "Sean's favorite Jonathan Glazer film and, to him, one of the best of the century; the long opera close-up is a career high. Auto-green."
        },
        {
          "title": "Margot at the Wedding",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "Noah Baumbach; she plays a vividly repellent single mother and never once tries to make you like her."
        },
        {
          "title": "Babygirl",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The week's subject, folded straight in despite the usual rule against inducting the newest release."
        }
      ]
    },
